85–1454":"1385–1454","1357–Male":"1357–Deceased","1436":"1436","1359":"1359","Abt 1409":"about 1409","1357":"1357","1454":"1454","1385":"1385","about 1357":"about 1357","about 1385":"about 1385","Sweden":"Sweden","Floda, Södermanland, Sweden":"Floda, Södermanland, Sweden","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Simonsson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Jewish (Ashkenazic): patronymic from the personal name   Simon   + <i>-son</i>.","English: habitational name from Simonstone in Aysgarth (North Yorkshire), from the Old English personal name <i>Sigemund</i> + Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone, rock’.","Americanized form (and a rare Swedish variant) of Swedish <b>Simonsson</b>: patronymic from the personal name   Simon  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Simison","meanings":["Scottish: shortened form of   Simonson  ."]},{"name":"Simon","meanings":["English (Lancashire), French, Walloon, Breton, German, Dutch, Hungarian, northern Italian, and Jewish (Ashkenazic); Spanish (<b>Simón</b>); Czech and Slovak (mainly <b>Šimon</b>); Slovenian, Croatian, and Rusyn (from Slovakia) (also <b>Šimon</b>): from the Biblical personal name, Hebrew <i>Shim‘on</i>, which is probably derived from the Hebrew verb <i>sham‘a</i> ‘to hearken’. In the Vulgate and in many vernacular versions of the Old Testament, this is usually rendered   Simeon  . In the Greek New Testament, however, the name occurs as <i>Simōn</i>, as a result of assimilation to the pre-existing Greek byname <i>Sīmōn</i> (from <i>sīmos</i> ‘snub-nosed’). Both <i>Simon</i> and <i>Simeon</i> were in use as personal names in western Europe from the Middle Ages onward. In Christendom the former was always more popular, at least in part because of its associations with the apostle Simon Peter, the brother of Andrew. In Britain there was also confusion from an early date with Anglo-Scandinavian forms of <i>Sigmund(r)</i> or <i>Sigmund</i> (see   Siegmund  ), a name whose popularity was reinforced at the Conquest by the Norman form <i>Simund</i>. In North America, this surname has also absorbed cognates from other languages, e.g. Italian   Simone  , Polish <b>Szymon</b>, Albanian   Simoni  , and Assyrian/Chaldean or Arabic <b>Shimun</b>,   Shamon  , or   Shamoun  , and also their derivatives (see examples at   Simons  ). See also   Shimon  .","History: André Simon <i>dit</i> Boucher from France married Marie Martin in Acadia <i>c.</i> 1688. François Simon from Saint-Pair-sur-Mer in Manche, France, married Marie-Dorothée Gagnon in Rivière-Ouelle, QC, in 1744."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1702076,"age":79,"year":"1436","julianDay":2245548,"title":"The Engelbrekt Rebellion","description":"Engelbrekt Engelbrektsson, a Swedish mine owner and statesman, led a rebellion against Eric of Pomerania, King of the Kalmar Union. Sweden was upset with the Danes' interference with Swedish exports and unjust collection of taxes. The Engelbrekt Rebellion led to the deposing of Eric of Pomerania and the eventual dissolution of the Kalmar Union.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Kettilbjörn Simonsson was born about 1357, in Sweden. He married Mrs Kettilbjorn Simonsson about 1409, in Sweden. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1357–":"umbes 1357–Surnud","1359–Female":"1359–Surnud","1385–1454":"1385–1454","1357–Male":"1357–Surnud","1436":"1436","1359":"1359","Abt 1409":"umbes 1409","1357":"1357","1454":"1454","1385":"1385","about 1357":"umbes 1357","about 1385":"umbes 1385","Sweden":"Rootsi","Floda, Södermanland, Sweden":"Floda, Södermanland, Rootsi"},"fi":{"about 1357–":"noin 1357–Kuollut","1359–Female":"1359–Kuollut","1385–1454":"1385–1454","1357–Male":"1357–Kuollut","1436":"1436","1359":"1359","Abt 1409":"noin 1409","1357":"1357","1454":"1454","1385":"1385","about 1357":"noin 1357","about 1385":"noin 1385","Sweden":"Ruotsi","Floda, Södermanland, Sweden":"Floda, Södermanland, Ruotsi"},"fr":{"about 1357–":"environ 1357–Déc